segments.text: And absolutely nothing was geared up for the expansion that was facing them.
They didn't have the faculty, they didn't have the facilities, they had nothing to adjust for that explosion of students that they faced beginning in 46.
But I was fortunate because I had the points to get out of the service very early.
22nd of September was pretty early after it ended.
And then number two, I had completed my pre-professional requirements with the exception of one chemistry course or something.
So I came and stopped by and talked to Dean Marsteller, showed him my transcript.
I don't know where I'd gotten that.
I guess I had the foresight to pick that up.
But I had my transcript, showed him what I'd completed.
And so, because I was out so early, there still weren't, there wasn't very many people applying at that point in time.
And because I had all the requirements, I just walked in school and said, sure, report next Monday.
Really?
So, I did.
By the next year or two, it was, it got very competitive to get in school.
Because there were only ten veterinary schools at that time.
But, uh,
That fall, I didn't have any trouble at all.
How many classmates did you have?
Well, I had, in the fall of 45, I started with a mixed class.
I'm going to guess there were about 40 or 45 of us all together, about half veterans and about half youngsters, young people that had just finished the two-year requirement in the Corps.
Right.
So about half that class in the fall of 45 was veterans, about half were young people.
Because I remember a lot of horseplay between the two groups.
The veterans were, I was probably one of the younger veterans.
And I guess I was, what, 22, 23 years old.
And I was one of the younger ones.
And some of the veterans went on up to 30, 35.
So it was a broad range of ages.
And of course, the poor kids were about 18 in those days.
Now, you had the requirements were done basically two years
of college.
As a matter of fact, on the books, you didn't even need two years of college.
And you never did receive a bachelor's degree.
What was your opinion of that?
And now what is it as a dean?
Well, I think we started promoting the bachelor's degree for students after we could no longer take them, all after two years.
when we could take the students after the required number of courses, the 66 hours that we have now, when we could admit them, I think that's a good program.
But when we started, we had to limit enrollment, and we could no longer admit all the well-qualified youngsters after two years.
Then we had to say, hey, you have to get onto a degree program.
and complete a bachelor's degree in some field of interest, whether it's animal science or agricultural economics or business or whatever.
Get a degree.
Get something.
Because you may not get into veterinary school, or you may not get in until you've had three or four years of college work.
So I believed in the bachelor's degree.
I never did get one, but I just
In fact, I tried to when I came back here and entered veterinary school.
I took a few more agricultural courses trying to qualify for the bachelor's degree by the time I graduated.
But I missed it by, I don't know, something like six or eight hours.
And it wasn't important enough to spend another semester.

Let's talk about the vet school when you came back in the 1940s, and let's compare not the tangibles, like how much it's changed as far as the size, and as far as the curriculum, we can read that out of the documents, but some of the intangibles, like the quality of instruction.
Could you compare what you thought was the quality of instruction back then versus today?
Yes, of course the quality of instruction from the technical standpoint
the young people today get so much better education in the technical aspects of our profession.
In surgery, anesthesiology, the education is a thousand times better than what we got.
More resources.
The resources are so much better.
The laboratories and equipment are so much better.
Everything, of course.
But, of course, 30 years or 35 years is a lot of time, too.
But
From the standpoint of the quality of teachers and of the sort of the intangibles of veterinary education, I'm not sure we've improved that much.
We had some great teachers.
We had people like John Miliff who headed anatomy, Pat Burns who headed physiology, Dick Turk in parasitology.
August Leonard in medicine.
Great men.
Because our classes were smaller, their influence on our lives was greater.
They had a tremendous impact on us as people, as future professionals.
I think maybe we've lost ground in that respect.
Because of the enlargement?
Because of the enlargement and because the youngsters do not get
as much of the professional integrity as we got from some of those giants of another era.
We have a lot of team teaching.
And especially under our accelerated program, where many times students really never got to know their teachers that well.
And they missed some things.
So on balance,
Terry, I'd say it's a trade-off.
We're doing a lot better in some areas, but nothing is all positive, just like the New Deal of the Great Society, you know.
Nothing's all positive.
True.
What about another intangible, and that is the quality of the students, your colleagues back then versus today?
Well, that's, again, a little bit hard to compare because
In the 40s and 50s, most of the young, and it was almost all young men, because women were not on the scene in our profession, only to a very limited degree.
The young men almost all came from the family farm, the small farm.
Most of them had a different
background in that different sense of values, a different approach to life.
It was pre-television era, pre-nuclear science era.
There was so much difference.
We were not as well prepared for college, I don't think, at least
Maybe we were as well prepared for what we were facing as the youngsters what they face today.
We did not have the in-depth mathematics that I know that was always a deficiency I had.
I never had calculus, and I should have had a deeper, much more in-depth training in mathematics.
I suppose that the young man and woman of the 40s and 50s was better, much more oriented in American agriculture than they are today.
Now where do you find that most of your students come from?
An awful lot of them come from the big cities.
Middle America and modest and large cities.
But we receive a lot of our students right out of Houston, Dallas, San Antonio, especially the young women.
A lot of them come from that background.
I'm not saying it's bad.
No, it's different, and that's the point.
It's different.
Now, let's talk about your favorite instructors.
Let's talk about some of the ones that you had in Millock.
I've interviewed him.
He was one of my favorites.
He gave an excellent interview.
We had a wonderful time.
A giant, strong-willed, very great teacher.
A good positive influence.
A conservative, very conservative man.
I'm sure you picked him.
But he was very able, broadly trained, probably one of the best educated men that I had.
Dick Turk,
in parasitology, a natural wit, a man who, if he had not gone to veterinary school, could have given Bob Hope some trouble as a showman, and one of the sharpest natural wits I've ever seen.
Excellent teacher.
Those men were professionals in that they had come through the school of hard knocks, and they taught us
A lot about surviving in the real world.
Dr. Burns, I had great respect for him.
I did not consider him to be such a great teacher.
He was very methodical.
I thought he worked a little bit too hard to keep students from cheating.
That was always kind of a humorous thing because he didn't tolerate anything.
He didn't tolerate any academic dishonesty.
Another man that I had great respect for didn't stay here very long after I left.
His name was George Eads.
E-A-D-S?
E-A-D, I believe.
E-D-D-S, that's the way he spelled his name.
Eads, E-D-D-S.
He's in Florida.
He has not retired.
Soon will, I guess.
He taught pharmacology, and he was a master disciplinarian
So many of the Aggies in that day dreaded his class and his course because he was very demanding.
But I never had any trouble with it.
In fact, I sort of enjoyed it because I enjoyed the subject.
His approach to teaching didn't bother me, but it did a lot of people.
What about Jaggie?
Dr. Jaggie was
I don't know.
I did not leave with as good of an impression of Dr. Jaggi as some people did, I suppose.
I did not think he was a bad teacher, but he always started off well organized.
The first two or three weeks of his course were usually good, but then after that it sort of tailed off.
I saw him as an average teacher.
Now did the dean at that time do any teaching?
Dr. Marsteller's health failed.
He was failing in health when I came back here.
I didn't realize it, but the next year he went, as we say in the veterinary slang, he went downhill fast, physically.
went on to disabled, became disabled, and was relieved of his administrative duties in 1946.
So I never had a course under Dr. Marsteller.
Now, a lot of my contemporaries did, but I didn't.
The acting dean for the next two years was a man by the name of Dunn, D-U-N-N, a pathologist, microbiologist, and I had courses under him.
He was an excellent teacher.
Remarkable that I had courses under him in pathology and radiology, and they were all top-line.
Excellent teacher.
And at that time, the dean taught at least one course?
Yes.
And is that today?
Well, I have a course called an orientation course in just a few, 15 lectures or so.
And when I can't get time, I sometimes go into the parasitology laboratory because that was my training, parasitology.
But I don't do much because the size of the program has increased.
And then the thing that just kills a dean and to a lesser degree department head today is the emphasis on accountability.
We are constantly reporting or writing proposals.
Paperwork, the load is unbelievable.
I often think what it would be like if Dr. Francis or Marsteller or some of those men came back and had to work as dean for a year today.
They'd either go mad or the program would change one or the other.
because the load of paper is unbelievable anymore.
And there's not very much we can do about it.
It comes from everywhere.
The federal government, the state government, and the university.
Basically an attempt to raise money?
A lot of this?
Oh, an awful lot of it is a result of federal regulations.
For example?
That start at every angle, you know, from the, well,
The best example I would give, Terry, would be to cite the fact that veterinary schools became eligible for some federal support under the Health Manpower Act, starting back about 65 or 66.
And then every other year or so, every third year,
There'd be a new Health Manpower Act.
So veterinary medicine qualified for first a little federal support under institutional grants and then under what we call capitation grants.
Never amounted to a whole lot of money.
I don't think we've ever gotten more than 6% to 8% of our budget from the federal government.
But that 6% or 8% brought an enormous
amount of problems of accountability.
Because not only... What did you do with that money?
Well, we have used it more or less for enrichment of our programs.
We have used it to support our Biomedical Learning Resource Center.
You may have visited it down in the basement where we have medical artists, medical illustrators, television...
engineers, and so on.
You'll have to stop by and look at it.
We've used it to support that unit.
We've used it a bit to support the residency training program that we've developed in the clinical areas.
So it's been an enrichment for us.
We have not used it to pay salaries of faculty because we never know.
One year for the next, we'd have it.
So we try to avoid that.
And we've used it to buy equipment, special equipment with, do some remodeling with in some areas.
We've used it in a lot of ways, but those have been the main ones.
But in the process, we've brought on an awful lot of accountability on ourselves.
Not only just with... What type of regulations?
Not only with regard to that, but we have to...
to show from almost every angle that we are not discriminating against women, against minorities, against this and against that.
And we find ourselves just submitting reports all the time.
And of course, they constantly keep the hammer over your head.
If you don't do it, you lose your federal support.
Now, I wouldn't want to imply that it's all federal either.
Because there's an awful lot of accountability coming from the state, such areas as the Coordinating Board of Higher Education.
They'll decide that you're going to account for this course that you're training or this one that you're not using or this doctoral program that is debatable and should it be deleted.
And so you find yourself just once right after the other.

And sometimes you couldn't really trace it back to the federal level, but it had been brought on by the federal level by a force that they're exerting against the coordinating board or against the legislative budget board or some other group that we live with.
And the result is a heck of a lot of paperwork.
A lot of paperwork.
And then, of course, had a lot of proposals, because we tried to get money from wherever we came.
And this has resulted in our doing some things that we never would have done a few years ago.
Because of the pressures to gain admission to the college, we have had to, or do we have to, but we elected to,
got a advisory committee to the college.

This is a 16-member advisory board that's made up about half from practicing veterinarians, and the other half come from commodity groups, powerful political groups in Texas, like the Texas Southwestern Cattle Raisers, Texas Dairy Association, those people.
Well, when we got an advisory board,
then almost immediately we had to educate that board to what we do.
So we had meeting after meeting.
We had to submit a lot of material to them to study about our admission system, our different programs we have at the college, our research program, our clinical teaching program.
Then we had them here repeatedly, several different meetings, in which we would present show and tells of what we're doing.
Because they had to, in order for them to be helpful, they had to learn what we're doing.
And then we have a development council now, which is another group that we're trying to use to help us raise monies from private sector.
But each time you bring those things on, you increase the paperwork in the needs office by geometrical levels.
So we find ourselves spending so much time trying to communicate.
Some of it is not mandatory.
Some of it we do ourselves because we need we have to do.
I wouldn't mean to imply that that uncle or somebody in Washington or somebody in Austin has a heavy hand on our necks to report.
That's only partially true.
Part of it we bring on ourselves.
To compete for funds.
That's right.
And to justify our programs and build the image of our programs in the state.
Now let's turn to the University of Missouri.
You left Texas A&M, your first job was at Missouri.
You stayed there for how many years, a number of years?
25 altogether, almost, 24 and a half.
Can you make some comparisons with their program and Texas A&M?
The program at Missouri was much, much smaller.
After I went to Missouri, I was in private practice for a brief period.
And then I went back to the university as a faculty member, a youngster.
Then I was gone two different times to graduate school.
Early 1940s, I went to Auburn, and later went to Minnesota.
And by the time I came back to Missouri, I enjoyed Missouri.
It's a great state, a great place to live.
A wonderful period of our lives was there, reared a family there.
It's middle American ever since, very conservative state.
The name show me is pretty well right.
lived in Columbia at the University of Missouri, an old, old university established in 1836, a very traditional university.
The values of academia as might be manifested at Harvard or Yale or somewhere is there because of its age and because it had the university tradition we've always
We're kind of amused at Texas A&M because it's a Johnny-come-lately to the university realm.
It was a military school prior to 1960, mid-'60s.
But as I mentioned, we always went back to Missouri.
I had the privilege there working under some very fine people, with some fine people.
Again, some old, rugged individuals of the veterinary profession.
But Missouri's program was, of course, new in 1950, almost.
It started in the late 40s.
When I went there in 1949 and joined the faculty, I think the total size of the faculty was about 15.
And we only took 30 students a year for a long time.
And even when the faculty got what we call big, about 30 people, it was small and conservative.
And we had, I think, the ability to get to know our students almost like our children.
We usually knew them by first names.
We knew their wives, how many children they had, because many of them were veterans in the early 50s.
So it was a very close personal element, a family-like environment.
How about the quality of instruction?
By today's standards, it wouldn't be good.
By the standards of 1950, it was adequate, not outstanding.
We didn't have a research program of any importance until early 1960.
So it was mostly just a teaching program, and a few people were doing a little bit of research.
Today's standards, it wouldn't be good.
But everything involved, and you can't compare Muhammad Ali with Jack Dempsey, for instance.
Exactly.
Exactly.
What about your graduate training?
Why did you decide to go to Auburn, and then why did you decide to go to Minnesota?
Minnesota?
All right.
I went to Auburn because my dean, Dean Holly Groth, had been at Auburn and had been a director of the federal laboratory there.
And he knew the young man who had just gotten his doctor of science degree from John Hopkins in parasitology, had a high regard for him, and he encouraged me to go to Auburn.
I did go there, and I never regretted it.
I moved ahead a bit as a result of that man's influence.
Dr. Wilford Bailey, who was my master's advisor at Auburn, was a young man and was full of drive, very progressive, a good scientist, and he had a good influence on me.
So I was pleased that I had the opportunity to go to Auburn.
Why didn't you stay there for a PhD?
They didn't have a PhD program in those days.
I had to have gone to Hopkins or somewhere at that time.
So I went back to the University of Missouri and worked for another six or eight years.
Then I realized that I needed more in-depth training in research, for research, and I also knew that
realize that I'm staying there doing the same thing year after year, slipping somewhat professionally.
So I looked around for a way to go to graduate school.
Minnesota was well-respected, and I thought in those days they had one of the first-rate graduate schools offered for veterinarians.
I went to Minnesota because I had a good working relationship between veterinary medicine and human medicine.
And I was able to do most of my work at the medical school at Minnesota, rather than the veterinary school.
At that time.
Strong research.
Mayo influence, you know, was very strong.
So I went to Minnesota for that reason.
Number two, because they had an arrangement where I didn't have to stay the whole time.
I could go there, complete my
residency requirements and then do my dissertation in absentia.
And I had a good arrangement at Missouri to do my dissertation.
It was close enough that I could keep close contact with my major professor.
And I was able to get a National Science Faculty Fellowship.
By that time, I had children getting a pretty good size and all the family responsibilities.
So that was the reason I went to Minnesota.
And what way did your graduate training then help you?
Yeah, that's a good question.
Because I went to graduate school and did my dissertation in absentia, completed that in 1965, and almost immediately went into administration.
Never did do much research.
I never, I have no...
claim to a research career at all.
I think the thing that helped me was it gave me a good respect for research and its importance in the educational process.
But I never had any great research accomplishments.
Never had time.
Immediately, I was named chairman of the department.
Well, actually, I moved into the dean's office a little bit before I was named head of the microbiology department.
And for about five years, I tried to do both, service head of the department and assistant dean, too.
And I finally decided I can't do that.
That's not good.
Killed you.
Killed you.
So I gave up the department headship in 69, I think it was.
and became associate dean for academic affairs.
Worked with admissions, curriculum, instruction.
I guess what I loved most that I've ever done.
I really enjoyed that.
Really?
Why do you say that?
Because it was still a small program and because you could get to know the?
Well, I enjoy veterinary medical education.
I believe it's important.
And those were the areas where I thought I could get the best
feeling and maybe have the best influence.
There's admission because your program's never better than the quality of young people you admit.
Absolutely.
And curriculum is vital because you have to constantly struggle to improve the curriculum and keep it relevant to the needs of the graduate.
And instruction is so vital because it needs a constant update if we've increased class size to keep the instructors reaching to the maximum.
the young people with the best education.
So I just feel a very important area.
I enjoyed it.
I worked in that area for nine years.
And sometimes after coming here, I always wished I had a job back.
But so it's very... Well, let's move to this job.
How did you get it?
How did I get it?
I don't know.
I really don't know.
Did you see an advertisement?
I never...
I never really aspired to be a dean.
